description: Borrowed into late Middle English from Late Latin īnscrūtābilis, from in- (“not”) + scrūtō (“to examine”), corresponding to in- +‎ scrutable

adjectives.description: inscrutable (comparative more inscrutable, superlative most inscrutable)

entries.meaning: Difficult or impossible to comprehend, fathom, or interpret.
examples: His inscrutable theories would years later become the foundation of a whole new science.

entries.meaning: One who or that which is inscrutable; a person, etc. that cannot be comprehended.
